evidence.text: I.  Throughout Decades of Federal Funding, the UC System Has Made Leading Contributions to Research that Benefit the Public
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: The UC System has made leading contributions to research that benefit the public.

evidence.text: The UC System has produced 70 Nobel Prize winners, 101 MacArthur “Genius” grant award winners, 66 National Medal of Science winners, and 42 Pulitzer Prize winners.
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: The UC System has produced 70 Nobel Prize winners, 101 MacArthur 'Genius' grant award winners, 66 National Medal of Science winners, and 42 Pulitzer Prize winners.

evidence.text: In the past 30 years, decades of UC cancer research has saved nearly 4 million lives.
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: The UC System has saved nearly 4 million lives through its research.

evidence.text: 80.  In the medical realm, UC System research has led to development of MRI machines, cochlear implants that restore hearing, a universal viral vaccine, a brain implant that prevents Parkinson’s symptoms, and the use of CRISPR gene‑editing to cure sickle cell disease.
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: The UC System has developed MRI machines, cochlear implants that restore hearing, a universal viral vaccine, a brain implant that prevents Parkinson’s symptoms, and CRISPR gene‑editing to cure sickle cell disease.

evidence.text: 94.  Congress also holds the power of the federal purse. Indeed, Congress’s powers to set the policies of the nation are at their apex when it comes to spending money, as the Constitution “exclusively grants the power of the purse to Congress, not the President.”
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: Congress has the power of the purse, and the President cannot unilaterally terminate grants.

evidence.text: 103.  For example, Executive Order No. 14151, dated January 20, 2025 and titled “Ending Radical and Wasteful Government DEI Programs and Preferencing,” instructs the Attorney General and others to “coordinate the termination of all discriminatory programs, including illegal DEI and ‘diversity, equity, inclusion, and accessibility’ (DEIA) mandates, policies, programs, preferences, and activities.”
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14151 (January 20, 2025) ordering federal agencies to terminate or reduce grants.

evidence.text: 104.  EO No. 14173, titled “Ending Illegal Discrimination and Restoring Merit‑Based Opportunity,” addresses purported “immoral race‑ and sex‑based preferences … The order requires the Director of OMB to “excise references to DEI and DEIA principles … from Federal acquisition, contracting, grants, and financial assistance procedures” and to “terminate all ‘diversity,’ ‘equity,’ ‘equitable decision‑making,’ ‘equitable deployment of financial and technical assistance,’ ‘advancing equity,’ and like mandates, requirements, programs, or activities.”
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14173 (January 20, 2025) ordering federal agencies to terminate equity‑related grants.

evidence.text: 105.  On January 20, 2025, Defendant Trump also issued EO No. 14168, “Defending Women from Gender Ideology Extremism and Restoring Biological Truth to the Federal Government,” directing that “federal funds shall not be used to promote gender ideology,”
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14168 (January 20, 2025) directing that federal funds shall not be used to promote gender ideology.

evidence.text: 106.  On January 20, 2025, Defendant Trump further issued EO No. 14154, “Unleashing American Energy,” which directed federal agencies to “immediately pause the disbursement of funds appropriated through the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 (Public Law 117‑169) or the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act (Public Law 117‑58).”
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14154 (January 20, 2025) directing federal agencies to pause disbursement of funds appropriated through the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 and the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act.

evidence.text: 107.  On February 19, 2025, Defendant Trump issued EO No. 14217, “Commencing the Reduction of the Federal Bureaucracy.” The EO deemed several government entities “unnecessary,” and directed that any non‑statutory components or functions be “eliminated.”
evidence.source_document: Amended Class Action Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14217 (February 19, 2025) ordering the elimination of non‑statutory components or functions, including grant requests.

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14238 (March 14, 2025) continuing the reduction of the federal bureaucracy.

add_extracted.value: President Trump issued Executive Order No. 14222 (February 26, 2025) ordering agencies to review existing grants with a view to termination.
